UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 468
1 provided upon a candidate, member of the candidate's family,
2 committee, or contributing organization, or any of their employees, paid
3 or unpaid, including: tickets to an event which is unrelated to a political
4 campaign or candidacy; items of personal property for distribution to
5 prospective voters except items bearing the name, likeness, or logo of a
6 candidate or a campaign-related communication; expenditures to
7 promote or oppose a candidacy for a leadership position in a
8 governmental, professional, or political organization, or other entity; and
9 equipment or appliances the primary use of which is for purposes
10 outside of the campaign.
11 (c) The provisions of KRS 121.190 notwithstanding, a candidate shall not be
12 required to include a disclaimer on campaign stationery purchased with funds
13 from his campaign account.
14 (2) A member of the General Assembly may utilize funds in his or her campaign
15 account to:
16 (a) Contribute up to five thousand dollars ($5,000) per year to a political party or
17 caucus campaign committee;
18 (b) Contribute directly to another candidate, slate of candidates, political party, or
19 caucus campaign committee until his or her campaign funds have been
20 exhausted and the account has been closed, if the amount of the contribution
21 does not exceed the contribution limits contained in KRS 121.150(6) and (11);
22 (c) Make allowable campaign expenditures in both election years and nonelection
23 years;
24 (d) Upon approval by the President of the Senate or the Speaker of the House of
25 Representatives, depending on the member's chamber:
26 1. Attend a conference, meeting, reception, or similar event; or
27 2. Attend an educational course or seminar that maintains or improves
Page 2 of 4
XXXX 12/18/2025 2:20 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 468
1 skills employed by the member in carrying out the duties of his or her
2 elective office; and
3 (e) Pay for fees incurred from legal services while defending a matter arising
4 from his or her campaign or election or the performance of his or her official
5 duties.
6 (3) (a) The use of campaign funds to pay for the reasonable costs of security
7 measures for a state candidate, officeholder, member of his or her family,
8 and employees of the candidate's campaign or the officeholder's office is an
9 allowable campaign expenditure, so long as the security measures address
10 ongoing dangers or threats that would not exist irrespective of the
11 individual's status or duties as a candidate or officeholder. Disbursements
12 for security measures shall:
13 1. Be for the usual and normal charge for such goods or services; and
14 2. Not exceed fifteen thousand dollars ($15,000) per fiscal year.
15 (b) As used in this subsection:
16 1. "Security measure" includes but is not limited to:
17 a. Nonstructural security devices, such as security hardware, locks,
18 alarm systems, motion detectors, and security camera systems;
19 b. Structural security devices, such as wiring, lighting, gates, doors,
20 and fencing, so long as such devices are intended solely to
21 provide security and not to improve the property or increase its
22 value;
23 c. Security personnel and services that are bona fide, legitimate,
24 and professional; and
25 d. Cybersecurity software, devices, and services; and
26 2. "Usual and normal charge" means:
27 a. In the case of goods, the price of those goods in the market in
Page 3 of 4
XXXX 12/18/2025 2:20 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 468
1 which they are ordinarily purchased; and
2 b. In the case of services, the hourly or piecework charge for the
3 services at a commercially reasonable rate prevailing at the time
4 the services are rendered.
5 (4)[(3)] The registry shall promulgate administrative regulations to implement and
6 enforce the provisions of subsection (1) of this section.
7 (5)[(4)] In lieu of the penalties provided in KRS 121.140 and 121.990 for a violation
8 of this section, the registry may, after hearing:
9 (a) For a violation which was not committed knowingly, order the violator to
10 repay the amount of campaign funds which were expended for other than
11 allowable campaign expenditures, and if not repaid within thirty (30) days,
12 may impose a fine of up to one hundred dollars ($100) for each day the
13 amount is not repaid, up to a maximum fine of one thousand dollars ($1,000);
14 and
15 (b) For a violation which was committed knowingly, in addition to referring the
16 matter for criminal prosecution, order the violator to repay the amount of
17 campaign funds which were expended for other than allowable campaign
18 expenditures, and if not repaid within thirty (30) days, may impose a fine of
19 up to one hundred dollars ($100) for each day the amount is not repaid, up to
20 a maximum fine of one thousand dollars ($1,000).
